    <h2 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Method 1: JazzCash (Recommended)</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">JazzCash is Pakistan's most widely used mobile wallet, with over 30 million users. It's free, instant, and works on any phone — even feature phones via USSD. Perfect for utility bills, mobile top-ups, and sending money.</p>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4"><strong>How to use:</strong></p>
    <ol class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600 mb-6 list-decimal list-inside">
      <li>Download JazzCash app (or dial <code class="bg-neutral-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded font-mono">*786#</code> on feature phone)</li>
      <li>Register with CNIC and Jazz number</li>
      <li>Load money via Jazz scratch card, bank transfer, or JazzCash shop</li>
      <li>Navigate to Utility Bills → select utility → enter reference number → confirm amount → enter PIN</li>
    </ol>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-6"><strong>Pros:</strong> Free, instant, no bank account needed, works on feature phones, available everywhere.<br>
    <strong>Cons:</strong> Requires Jazz SIM; weekly transaction limits (Rs. 50,000 for basic account).</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Method 2: EasyPaisa</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">EasyPaisa is Telenor's mobile wallet, second-largest after JazzCash. Same features and convenience — best for Telenor users or anyone wanting a backup mobile wallet.</p>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4"><strong>How to use:</strong></p>
    <ol class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600 mb-6 list-decimal list-inside">
      <li>Download EasyPaisa app (or dial <code class="bg-neutral-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded font-mono">*786*1#</code> on feature phone)</li>
      <li>Register with CNIC and Telenor number</li>
      <li>Load money via Telenor scratch card, bank transfer, or EasyPaisa shop</li>
      <li>Navigate to Bills → select utility → enter reference number → confirm → enter PIN</li>
    </ol>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-6"><strong>Pros:</strong> Free, instant, no bank account, works on feature phones.<br>
    <strong>Cons:</strong> Requires Telenor SIM; same weekly transaction limits as JazzCash.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Method 3: Bank Mobile Apps</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">All major Pakistani banks offer free bill payment through their mobile apps. Best for larger bills (mobile wallets have transaction limits) and consumers who already bank online.</p>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4"><strong>Supported banks:</strong> HBL, UBL, MCB, Bank Alfalah, Meezan, Faysal, Allied Bank, Bank of Punjab, Bank of Khyber, Habib Metro, Askari Bank, Standard Chartered.</p>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4"><strong>How to use:</strong></p>
    <ol class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600 mb-6 list-decimal list-inside">
      <li>Download your bank's mobile app</li>
      <li>Activate mobile banking through your bank branch or ATM</li>
      <li>Login with credentials and OTP</li>
      <li>Navigate to Payments → Utility Bills → select category → select company → enter reference number → confirm</li>
    </ol>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-6"><strong>Pros:</strong> Free, instant, higher transaction limits (up to Rs. 1 million), one-stop for all financial needs.<br>
    <strong>Cons:</strong> Requires bank account, smartphone, and mobile banking activation.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Method 4: Bank Branch (Cash Payment)</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Traditional method still preferred by senior citizens and consumers without bank accounts. Bring your printed bill (or duplicate PDF) to any branch of HBL, UBL, MCB, NBP, or Bank Alfalah.</p>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-6"><strong>Pros:</strong> Free, accepts cash, available everywhere.<br>
    <strong>Cons:</strong> Long queues near due dates, limited banking hours (9 AM – 5 PM), payment reflects in 4 hours.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Method 5: 1Bill / Infinia Shops</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Over 100,000 shops across Pakistan display the 1Bill or Infinia logo and accept utility bill payments in cash. Convenient for after-hours payment or consumers without bank accounts.</p>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-6"><strong>Pros:</strong> Open late (often until 11 PM), no bank account needed, available in remote areas.<br>
    <strong>Cons:</strong> Rs. 30–50 fee per transaction, payment reflects in 12–24 hours, receipt quality varies.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Method 6: ATM</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Most bank ATMs accept utility bill payments via debit card. Useful for after-hours payment when you have a debit card but no mobile banking.</p>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-6"><strong>Pros:</strong> Free, instant, available 24/7.<br>
    <strong>Cons:</strong> Need debit card and PIN; not all ATMs support bill payment — check your bank's website for supported ATM locations.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Method 7: NADRA e-Sahulat</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">NADRA's e-Sahulat centers accept utility bill payments in cash. Especially useful in rural areas where banks and 1Bill shops are scarce.</p>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-6"><strong>Pros:</strong> Available in remote areas, no bank account needed.<br>
    <strong>Cons:</strong> Rs. 30 fee, payment reflects in 24–48 hours, limited NADRA centers in big cities.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Method 8: Post Office</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Pakistan Post offices accept utility bill payments at their counters. Oldest method still in use — mainly relevant for rural consumers.</p>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-6"><strong>Pros:</strong> Available in every tehsil, including very remote areas.<br>
    <strong>Cons:</strong> Rs. 20 fee, payment reflects in 2–3 days, very slow — avoid for time-sensitive payments.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Method 9: Utility Customer Service Center</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Every utility (LESCO, IESCO, SNGPL, K-Electric, etc.) has its own payment counter at the customer service center. Payments reflect instantly — best for last-day payments or when you have disputes.</p>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-6"><strong>Pros:</strong> Free, instant reflection, staff can resolve disputes on the spot.<br>
    <strong>Cons:</strong> Limited locations (only major cities), limited hours (9 AM – 5 PM).</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Method 10: Credit Card via Utility Website</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Most utilities (PTCL, K-Electric, SNGPL) accept credit/debit card payments directly on their websites. Useful if you want to earn credit card reward points or use international cards.</p>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-6"><strong>Pros:</strong> Free, instant, reward points on credit card.<br>
    <strong>Cons:</strong> Requires credit/debit card, website interface can be clunky, possible transaction limits.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Which Method Should You Choose?</h2>
    <ul class="space-y-3 text-neutral-600 mb-6 list-disc list-inside">
      <li><strong>Most users:</strong> JazzCash or EasyPaisa — free, instant, no bank account needed.</li>
      <li><strong>Bank account holders:</strong> Your bank's mobile app — higher limits, one-stop solution.</li>
      <li><strong>Senior citizens / no smartphone:</strong> Bank branch or 1Bill shop — pay in cash with help.</li>
      <li><strong>Last-day payment:</strong> Utility customer service center — instant reflection.</li>
      <li><strong>Rural areas:</strong> NADRA e-Sahulat or post office — only options in some areas.</li>
      <li><strong>Large bills (Rs. 100,000+):</strong> Bank mobile app — no transaction limit issues.</li>
      <li><strong>Credit card reward seekers:</strong> Utility website with credit card.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-xl font-heading font-bold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-3 mb-10">
      <details class="faq-item"><summary class="faq-question">What are the ways to pay utility bills in Pakistan?</summary><div class="px-4 pb-4 text-sm text-neutral-600">You can pay utility bills via: (1) Mobile wallets (JazzCash, EasyPaisa), (2) Bank mobile apps (HBL, UBL, MCB, etc.), (3) Bank branches (cash payment), (4) 1Bill shops, (5) ATMs, (6) NADRA e-Sahulat, (7) Post offices, (8) Official utility customer service centers, (9) Credit card through utility websites.</div></details>
      <details class="faq-item"><summary class="faq-question">Which bill payment method is free?</summary><div class="px-4 pb-4 text-sm text-neutral-600">Free methods: JazzCash, EasyPaisa, all bank mobile apps, bank branch cash payment (HBL, UBL, MCB, NBP), ATMs, utility customer service centers. Paid methods: 1Bill shops (Rs. 30-50), NADRA e-Sahulat (Rs. 30), Post office (Rs. 20).</div></details>
      <details class="faq-item"><summary class="faq-question">Which bill payment method is fastest?</summary><div class="px-4 pb-4 text-sm text-neutral-600">Fastest methods (instant reflection): JazzCash, EasyPaisa, bank mobile apps, ATMs, credit card on utility website. Slowest: 1Bill shops (12-24 hours), NADRA e-Sahulat (24-48 hours), post office (2-3 days).</div></details>
      <details class="faq-item"><summary class="faq-question">Can I pay bills without bank account?</summary><div class="px-4 pb-4 text-sm text-neutral-600">Yes. Use JazzCash or EasyPaisa mobile wallets (no bank account needed — just a CNIC and active SIM). You can also pay cash at 1Bill shops, NADRA e-Sahulat centers, post offices, or utility customer service centers.</div></details>
      <details class="faq-item"><summary class="faq-question">Which bills can be paid online in Pakistan?</summary><div class="px-4 pb-4 text-sm text-neutral-600">All major utility bills can be paid online: electricity (LESCO, IESCO, FESCO, all DISCOs, K-Electric), gas (SNGPL, SSGC), water (WASA Lahore/Faisalabad/Rawalpindi), telephone (PTCL), mobile postpaid (Jazz, Zong, Telenor, Ufone), internet (Nayatel, Transworld, Wateen).</div></details>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-2xl p-6 mb-8 text-center">
      <h2 class="font-bold text-xl text-primary-900 mb-2">Check Your Bill First</h2>
      <p class="text-primary-700 mb-4 text-sm">View your bill amount before paying through any method.</p>
      <a href="/electricity/" class="inline-block bg-primary-700 text-white px-8 py-3 rounded-xl font-bold text-lg hover:bg-primary-800 transition-colors">
        Browse All Bill Checkers &rarr;
      </a>
